  <static seed="38" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/MultiplyFractions30.pg">
    <statement><p>Multiply: <m>\displaystyle{5\cdot \frac{2}{7} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{10}{7}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To multiply an integer with a fraction, first we change the integer into a fraction by rewriting it with a <lq/>1<rq/> as the denominator:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{5 = \frac{5}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, simply multiply both numerators and both denominators:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   5\cdot \frac{2}{7} 
       \amp = \frac{5}{1} \cdot \frac{2}{7} \\
       \amp = \frac{5\cdot2}{1 \cdot 7} \\
       \amp = \frac{10}{7}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is <m>\displaystyle{\frac{10}{7}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
